{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Fn1tSyqBJLHPXtBARvpzae","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FzPfymY1qpgvY5yGkZeFRZ","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/root/research/results.md","content":"# Discrete Diffusion World Models for Atari: Preliminary Results\n\n## Overview\n\nThis work implements and evaluates a **masked discrete diffusion world model** for Atari game environments, specifically trained on Breakout. The approach replaces DIAMOND's continuous diffusion (EDM-style) with a discrete diffusion process (MDLM-style) operating on VQ-VAE tokenized frames.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Visual Tokenizer (PatchVQ-VAE)\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Input | 64×64×3 RGB frames |\n| Patch size | 4×4×3 = 48 dimensions |\n| Token grid | 16×16 = 256 tokens per frame |\n| Codebook | 512 codes, 256-dim embeddings |\n| Encoder | 3-layer MLP (48→256→256→256) |\n| Decoder | 3-layer MLP (256→256→256→48) |\n| Parameters | 0.4M |\n| Recon. PSNR | 55.58 dB |\n| Codebook util. | 100% (512/512) |\n\n### Discrete Diffusion Transformer\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Type | Masked discrete diffusion (MDLM) |\n| Backbone | Bidirectional Transformer |\n| Layers | 8 |\n| Model dim | 512 |\n| Attention heads | 8 |\n| Parameters | 48.1M |\n| Conditioning | AdaLN (action + timestep) |\n| Context | Cross-attention to prev frame |\n| Masking schedule | Cosine |\n| Training loss | Cross-entropy on masked tokens |\n\n### DIAMOND (Baseline)\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Type | Continuous diffusion (EDM) |\n| Backbone | U-Net with AdaGroupNorm |\n| Channels | [64, 64, 64, 64] |\n| Denoising steps | 3 |\n| Training loss | MSE |\n\n## Training\n\n**Data**: 100,000 frames from Breakout (random policy), 4 actions\n\n### Loss Curve\n*(See figures/plots/training_loss.png)*\n\n| Step | Loss (CE) | Notes |\n|------|-----------|-------|\n| 100 | 3.96 | Early warmup |\n| 500 | 0.092 | Rapid convergence |\n| 1,000 | 0.038 | |\n| 5,000 | 0.008 | |\n| 10,000 | 0.006 | Good sample quality |\n\n## Quantitative Results\n\n*(To be filled after evaluation completes)*\n\n### Frame Prediction Quality (Next-Frame PSNR/SSIM)\n\n| Denoising Steps | PSNR (dB) | SSIM | LPIPS ↓ |\n|----------------|-----------|------|---------|\n| 4 | TBD | TBD | - |\n| 8 | TBD | TBD | TBD |\n| 16 | TBD | TBD | - |\n| 32 | TBD | TBD | - |\n\n### Inference Speed (H100)\n\n| Denoising Steps | FPS | ms/frame |\n|----------------|-----|----------|\n| 4 | TBD | TBD |\n| 8 | TBD | TBD |\n| 16 | TBD | TBD |\n| 32 | TBD | TBD |\n\n### Long-Horizon Quality\n\n*(See figures/plots/long_horizon.png)*\n\n## Qualitative Results\n\n*(See figures/samples/ for generated frame comparisons)*\n\nEach image shows: **Previous Frame | Ground Truth | Prediction**\n\n## Key Findings\n\n1. **VQ-VAE tokenizer achieves near-lossless reconstruction** (55.58 dB PSNR) with full codebook utilization, validating the discrete tokenization approach.\n\n2. **Discrete diffusion training converges rapidly** — loss drops from ~4 to ~0.006 within 10k steps, suggesting that the masked prediction task on VQ-VAE tokens is well-suited for Atari frame prediction.\n\n3. **TBD**: Comparison with DIAMOND on visual quality metrics.\n\n4. **TBD**: Analysis of denoising steps vs quality tradeoff.\n\n5. **TBD**: Long-horizon rollout stability.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. **Scale training**: Train for longer on more diverse data (multiple games)\n2. **URSA-style metric path**: Replace uniform categorical noise with structured transitions through codebook embedding space\n3. **AR-DF temporal tube masking**: Apply same spatial mask across frames to prevent temporal shortcut learning\n4. **RL agent training**: Train an RL agent within the world model (like DIAMOND does)\n5. **Multiple games**: Test generalization across Pong, MsPacman, etc.\n\n---\n\n*Generated: 2026-04-05*\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":625,"cache_read_input_tokens":125461,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":625},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6eb3f8f9-70a7-4c62-8ed1-8dd1b9e7b463","uuid":"9fd90af2-e44e-4f07-ba79-040f76db7805"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FzPfymY1qpgvY5yGkZeFRZ","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /root/research/results.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6eb3f8f9-70a7-4c62-8ed1-8dd1b9e7b463","uuid":"dd11104f-6c4e-47cc-aade-e2e9e5d9086c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T09:43:23.797Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/root/research/results.md","content":"# Discrete Diffusion World Models for Atari: Preliminary Results\n\n## Overview\n\nThis work implements and evaluates a **masked discrete diffusion world model** for Atari game environments, specifically trained on Breakout. The approach replaces DIAMOND's continuous diffusion (EDM-style) with a discrete diffusion process (MDLM-style) operating on VQ-VAE tokenized frames.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Visual Tokenizer (PatchVQ-VAE)\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Input | 64×64×3 RGB frames |\n| Patch size | 4×4×3 = 48 dimensions |\n| Token grid | 16×16 = 256 tokens per frame |\n| Codebook | 512 codes, 256-dim embeddings |\n| Encoder | 3-layer MLP (48→256→256→256) |\n| Decoder | 3-layer MLP (256→256→256→48) |\n| Parameters | 0.4M |\n| Recon. PSNR | 55.58 dB |\n| Codebook util. | 100% (512/512) |\n\n### Discrete Diffusion Transformer\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Type | Masked discrete diffusion (MDLM) |\n| Backbone | Bidirectional Transformer |\n| Layers | 8 |\n| Model dim | 512 |\n| Attention heads | 8 |\n| Parameters | 48.1M |\n| Conditioning | AdaLN (action + timestep) |\n| Context | Cross-attention to prev frame |\n| Masking schedule | Cosine |\n| Training loss | Cross-entropy on masked tokens |\n\n### DIAMOND (Baseline)\n| Component | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Type | Continuous diffusion (EDM) |\n| Backbone | U-Net with AdaGroupNorm |\n| Channels | [64, 64, 64, 64] |\n| Denoising steps | 3 |\n| Training loss | MSE |\n\n## Training\n\n**Data**: 100,000 frames from Breakout (random policy), 4 actions\n\n### Loss Curve\n*(See figures/plots/training_loss.png)*\n\n| Step | Loss (CE) | Notes |\n|------|-----------|-------|\n| 100 | 3.96 | Early warmup |\n| 500 | 0.092 | Rapid convergence |\n| 1,000 | 0.038 | |\n| 5,000 | 0.008 | |\n| 10,000 | 0.006 | Good sample quality |\n\n## Quantitative Results\n\n*(To be filled after evaluation completes)*\n\n### Frame Prediction Quality (Next-Frame PSNR/SSIM)\n\n| Denoising Steps | PSNR (dB) | SSIM | LPIPS ↓ |\n|----------------|-----------|------|---------|\n| 4 | TBD | TBD | - |\n| 8 | TBD | TBD | TBD |\n| 16 | TBD | TBD | - |\n| 32 | TBD | TBD | - |\n\n### Inference Speed (H100)\n\n| Denoising Steps | FPS | ms/frame |\n|----------------|-----|----------|\n| 4 | TBD | TBD |\n| 8 | TBD | TBD |\n| 16 | TBD | TBD |\n| 32 | TBD | TBD |\n\n### Long-Horizon Quality\n\n*(See figures/plots/long_horizon.png)*\n\n## Qualitative Results\n\n*(See figures/samples/ for generated frame comparisons)*\n\nEach image shows: **Previous Frame | Ground Truth | Prediction**\n\n## Key Findings\n\n1. **VQ-VAE tokenizer achieves near-lossless reconstruction** (55.58 dB PSNR) with full codebook utilization, validating the discrete tokenization approach.\n\n2. **Discrete diffusion training converges rapidly** — loss drops from ~4 to ~0.006 within 10k steps, suggesting that the masked prediction task on VQ-VAE tokens is well-suited for Atari frame prediction.\n\n3. **TBD**: Comparison with DIAMOND on visual quality metrics.\n\n4. **TBD**: Analysis of denoising steps vs quality tradeoff.\n\n5. **TBD**: Long-horizon rollout stability.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. **Scale training**: Train for longer on more diverse data (multiple games)\n2. **URSA-style metric path**: Replace uniform categorical noise with structured transitions through codebook embedding space\n3. **AR-DF temporal tube masking**: Apply same spatial mask across frames to prevent temporal shortcut learning\n4. **RL agent training**: Train an RL agent within the world model (like DIAMOND does)\n5. **Multiple games**: Test generalization across Pong, MsPacman, etc.\n\n---\n\n*Generated: 2026-04-05*\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
