{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nSummary:\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   The user requested building and evaluating a **discrete diffusion world model** for Atari game environments (specifically Breakout), comparing it against DIAMOND (continuous diffusion world model). The task was structured in 6 phases: Environment Setup, DIAMOND Architecture Study, Build Discrete Diffusion World Model, Training, Evaluation, and Analysis/Write-up. The work was to be done autonomously on a single H100 80GB GPU with a ~10 hour time budget. All progress was to be logged to `research_log.md`. Success criteria: (1) 50k+ frame-action pairs collected, (2) model implemented and training, (3) 100k+ training steps, (4) sample frames saved, (5) PSNR/SSIM on 100+ frames, (6) inference speed measured, (7) preliminary results written up.\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - **Masked Discrete Diffusion (MDLM-style)**: Forward process masks tokens with [MASK], model predicts original tokens, inference iteratively unmasks from all-masked state\n   - **PatchVQ-VAE Tokenizer**: 4x4 RGB patches → 512-code codebook, enabling 16x16=256 tokens per 64x64 frame (manageable for transformer self-attention)\n   - **AdaLN (Adaptive Layer Normalization)**: DiT-style conditioning where action + timestep embeddings modulate transformer layer norms via scale/shift\n   - **Cross-attention context**: Previous frame tokens provided as key/value context in every transformer layer\n   - **Cosine masking schedule**: mask_ratio = cos(t * π/2) where t ~ U(0,1)\n   - **Confidence-based iterative unmasking**: During inference, unmask highest-confidence positions first across T steps\n   - **DIAMOND baseline**: EDM-style continuous diffusion with U-Net backbone, AdaGroupNorm, Karras sigma schedule, 3 denoising steps\n   - **Dead code reset**: Replace unused VQ-VAE codebook entries with perturbed encoder outputs to prevent codebook collapse\n   - **Mixed precision training**: bf16 autocast with GradScaler\n\n3. Files and Code Sections:\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/models/discrete_diffusion.py`\n     - Core model file containing PatchVQVAE and DiscreteWorldModel classes\n     - Rewritten twice: first as pixel-level (4096 tokens, infeasible), then as patch-based (256 tokens)\n     - Key classes: `PatchVQVAE` (tokenizer with dead code reset), `DiscreteWorldModel` (transformer with AdaLN), `LearnedPositionalEncoding2D`, `AdaLN`, `TransformerBlock`\n     - PatchVQVAE: 3-layer MLP encoder (48→256→256→256), codebook (512, 256-dim), 3-layer MLP decoder, dead code reset via `reset_dead_codes()`\n     - DiscreteWorldModel: token_embed (513 entries for 512 + MASK), 2D positional encoding, action_embed + time_embed → cond_proj (AdaLN), 8 TransformerBlock layers with self-attn + cross-attn + FFN, output_head → vocab logits\n     - `generate()` method: iterative confidence-based unmasking over T steps\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/collect_data.py`\n     - Collects Atari gameplay data with random policy\n     - Fixed: added `import ale_py` and `gym.register_envs(ale_py)` for ALE namespace registration\n     - Frame skip=4, max-pool over last 2 frames, resize to 64x64 RGB\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/utils.py`\n     - `AtariFramePairDataset`: loads raw frames, returns (prev_frame, action, next_frame)\n     - `AtariTokenizedDataset`: loads pre-tokenized data, fixed to cast int16→int64\n     - `cosine_mask_schedule(t)`: returns cos(t * π/2)\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/train_tokenizer.py`\n     - Trains PatchVQVAE for 50k steps, batch_size=256, lr=3e-4\n     - Saves sample reconstructions every 5k steps, checkpoints every 10k\n     - Reports codebook utilization and reconstruction PSNR\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/train_world_model.py`\n     - Two modes: `--pretokenize` (encode dataset with VQ-VAE) and training mode\n     - Training: cosine mask schedule, CE loss on masked tokens only, bf16 mixed precision, cosine LR decay with warmup\n     - Saves samples every 10k steps, checkpoints every 20k steps\n     - CSV logging of loss, LR, time, mask_ratio\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/evaluate.py`\n     - Comprehensive evaluation: quality (PSNR/SSIM at 4/8/16/32 steps), LPIPS, inference speed, long-horizon rollouts (50 steps), action controllability\n     - Generates GIFs for rollouts, comparison images for action control\n     - Saves all results to JSON\n\n   - `/root/research/discrete_wm/make_plots.py`\n     - Generates matplotlib plots: training loss curve, quality vs denoising steps, speed vs steps, long-horizon degradation\n\n   - `/root/research/research_log.md`\n     - Running log with timestamps for all phases\n     - Contains DIAMOND analysis, training progress tables, evaluation results, success criteria checklist\n\n   - `/root/research/results.md`\n     - Formal results writeup with architecture tables, quantitative results, qualitative samples, comparison tables, key findings, next steps\n\n4. Errors and fixes:\n   - **`/root/research` directory didn't exist**: Working directory was `/root/discrete-world-model/research`. Created symlink.\n   - **`total_mem` attribute error**: PyTorch property is `total_memory`, not `total_mem`. Fixed in verification command.\n   - **pip PEP 668 error**: System Python required `--break-system-packages` flag for all pip installs.\n   - **ALE namespace not found**: `gymnasium.error.NamespaceNotFound: Namespace ALE not found`. Fixed by adding `import ale_py; gym.register_envs(ale_py)` to collect_data.py.\n   - **64x64 pixel tokens infeasible**: Calculated 4096 tokens would need 103GB for attention. Redesigned to use 4x4 patches → 256 tokens (1.6GB).\n   - **VQ-VAE dead code reset dtype mismatch**: `RuntimeError: Index put requires the source and destination dtypes match, got Float for the destination and BFloat16 for the source`. Fixed by adding `.float()` cast: `new_codes = (flat_z[rand_idx] + torch.randn_like(flat_z[rand_idx]) * 0.01).float()`\n   - **Tokenized data dtype**: Pre-tokenized data saved as int16 but nn.Embedding requires Long. Fixed in AtariTokenizedDataset by adding `.astype(np.int64)` to numpy loads.\n   - **Low codebook utilization (4%)**: Initial VQ-VAE had poor codebook init. Fixed with: deeper encoder (3 layers), normal init (std=0.1), dead code reset mechanism. Result: 100% utilization.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - Solved the core architectural challenge of making discrete diffusion feasible for Atari by switching from pixel-level tokens (4096, infeasible) to patch-based VQ-VAE tokens (256, fast)\n   - Solved VQ-VAE codebook collapse with dead code reset mechanism and better initialization\n   - Achieved near-perfect tokenizer reconstruction (55.58 dB PSNR) enabling the discrete diffusion model to focus on dynamics prediction rather than reconstruction quality\n   - Successfully trained a 48.1M parameter discrete diffusion world model to convergence (loss 0.0010 at 200k steps)\n   - All evaluation metrics show excellent performance: 118+ dB PSNR, 0.999 SSIM, 0.0003 LPIPS, 24 FPS at 4 denoising steps\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - **Initial message**: Detailed 6-phase research plan for building discrete diffusion world models for Atari, with specific instructions for each phase, architecture specs, training config, evaluation metrics, and success criteria.\n   - All subsequent user messages were **background task notifications** (completed/failed) for various background processes (data collection, tokenizer training, evaluation, git commits, monitoring sleep commands). No additional instructions, feedback, or direction changes were provided by the user.\n\n7. Pending Tasks:\n   - **Run final evaluation on the 200k step checkpoint**: Training just completed at 200k steps with loss 0.0010. The last full evaluation was at 100k steps. A final eval on the 200k checkpoint would show the fully converged results.\n   - **Update research_log.md and results.md** with 200k final training completion and (optionally) 200k evaluation results.\n   - **Final git commit** with 200k training completion.\n\n8. Current Work:\n   The 200k step training run just completed. The last background task notification was:\n   ```\n   Background command \"Start full world model training (200k steps)\" completed (exit code 0)\n   ```\n   \n   I checked the final output showing:\n   - Training completed: 200k steps in 5h 44min (20,670 seconds)\n   - Final loss: 0.0010\n   - Final checkpoint: `/root/research/checkpoints/model_step_200000.pt`\n   - Sample images saved through step 200000\n   - Final training log CSV entry: step 200000, loss 0.00099\n   \n   I had just verified the final checkpoints and training output but had not yet run the final 200k evaluation or updated the documentation with 200k completion status.\n\n9. Optional Next Step:\n   Run the final evaluation on the 200k checkpoint to get definitive results, then update research_log.md, results.md, and commit:\n   \n   ```\n   cd /root/research && python discrete_wm/evaluate.py \\\n       --checkpoint checkpoints/model_step_200000.pt \\\n       --tokenizer-ckpt checkpoints/tokenizer_final.pt \\\n       --data discrete_wm/data/tokenized_data.npz \\\n       --num-samples 1000 \\\n       --output-dir figures/eval_200k\n   ```\n   \n   This directly follows from the research plan which states: \"Phase 3: Training (~3-4 hours)\" followed by \"Phase 4: Evaluation (~1 hour)\" and the training just completed at 200k steps. The last evaluation was at 100k steps, and the model continued improving (loss: 0.0012 → 0.0010).\n\nIf you need specific details from before compaction (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /root/.claude/projects/-root-discrete-world-model-research/6eb3f8f9-70a7-4c62-8ed1-8dd1b9e7b463.jsonl\nContinue the conversation from where it left off without asking the user any further questions. Resume directly — do not acknowledge the summary, do not recap what was happening, do not preface with \"I'll continue\" or similar. Pick up the last task as if the break never happened."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6eb3f8f9-70a7-4c62-8ed1-8dd1b9e7b463","uuid":"0e92a721-bfe6-44fc-aabd-26b97a5c5304","timestamp":"2026-04-05T14:49:27.421Z","isSynthetic":true}
