{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HAy5znFZCciTDC6PkXtfio","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Excellent! The 200k evaluation is complete. Let me summarize the key results:\n\n**Quality (200k vs 100k)**:\n| Metric | 100k | 200k | Change |\n|--------|------|------|--------|\n| PSNR (4 steps) | 118.6 | 119.1 | +0.5 |\n| PSNR (8 steps) | 118.1 | 118.3 | +0.2 |\n\n\n| PSNR (16 steps) | 118.9 | 119.1 | +0.2 |\n| PSNR (32 steps) | 118.4 | 119.1 | +0.7 |\n| SSIM (best) | 0.9991 | 0.9991 | Same |\n| LPIPS (8 steps) | 0.0003 | 0.0004 | Slightly worse (within noise) |\n\nThe quality metrics show consistent improvements across PSNR at different step counts, with the 32-step configuration gaining the most. SSIM remains maxed out and LPIPS degradation is negligible. Now I'm looking at the speed benchmarks to see if the 200k training also improved inference performance.\n\nThe speed gains are substantial—nearly 2x faster across all step counts—though this is likely an artifact of GPU warmth and caching effects rather than a true architectural improvement. The long-horizon evaluation shows the 200k model achieving significantly higher PSNR at step 1, suggesting better quality in the early diffusion steps.\n\nLooking at the step 50 results, the 200k model actually performs worse (41.4 vs 50.8), which is counterintuitive. This could indicate the model is converging too sharply early on, causing divergence at longer horizons, or it might just be measurement noise. Action controllability remains essentially flat at 0.19-0.20, so no meaningful change there.\n\nNow I need to update the research log and results documentation with these 200k findings, regenerate the comparison plots, and commit everything.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7107,"cache_read_input_tokens":34330,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_to